<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><a title=3D"OVACEN calculators section" hr=
ef=3D"https://ovacen.com/calculator/#calculators">Do you want to see other =
calculation tools?</a></p>
<p>The following <a href=3D"https://ovacen.com/en/calculator/">online calcu=
lator</a> is a tool to calculate the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Sphere" rel=3D"noopener"><strong>volume of a sphere</strong></a>, based =
on the radius of the sphere. The application calculates the volume of the s=
phere using the formula <strong>Volume =3D (4/3) =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 radiu=
s=C2=B3</strong>. This allows calculating the volume of any sphere, whether=
 small or large.</p>
<p>Additionally, as an option, the <strong>sphere volume calculator</strong=
> also allows calculating its capacity from the diameter and its circumfere=
nce.</p>
<h3><strong>How does the sphere volume calculator work?</strong></h3>
<p>To <strong>calculate the volume of the sphere</strong>, follow these ste=
ps:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Enter the value of the radius (r):</strong>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>Enter the radius of the sphere in the indicated field and select the di=
mension unit if necessary. Optionally, you can use the diameter and circumf=
erence to calculate the interior space of the sphere.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Calculate the volume of the sphere:</strong>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>The calculator will automatically perform the calculation and display t=
he <strong>volume of the sphere</strong> according to the selected unit.</l=
i>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<p>We remind you that the <strong>formulas to calculate spherical volume</s=
trong> vary depending on the distance to be used:</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_45161" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-4516=
1" style=3D"width: 929px" class=3D"wp-caption aligncenter"><picture decodin=
g=3D"async" class=3D"wp-image-45161 size-full">
<source type=3D"image/webp" data-lazy-srcset=3D"https://ovacen.com/wp-conte=
nt/uploads/2025/01/formulas-for-calculating-sphere-volume.jpg.webp 939w, ht=
tps://ovacen.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/formulas-for-calculating-sphere=
-volume-649x383.jpg.webp 649w, https://ovacen.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/0=
1/formulas-for-calculating-sphere-volume-669x395.jpg.webp 669w, https://ova=
cen.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/formulas-for-calculating-sphere-volume-7=
68x453.jpg.webp 768w" srcset=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http:/=
/www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20939%20554'%3E%3C/svg%3E" data-la=
zy-sizes=3D"(max-width: 939px) 100vw, 939px">
<img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://=
www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20939%20554'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt=3D"f=
ormulas for calculating any volume of a sphere" width=3D"939" height=3D"554=
" data-lazy-srcset=3D"https://ovacen.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/formula=
s-for-calculating-sphere-volume.jpg 939w, https://ovacen.com/wp-content/upl=
oads/2025/01/formulas-for-calculating-sphere-volume-649x383.jpg 649w, https=
://ovacen.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/formulas-for-calculating-sphere-vo=
lume-669x395.jpg 669w, https://ovacen.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/formul=
as-for-calculating-sphere-volume-768x453.jpg 768w" data-lazy-sizes=3D"(max-=
width: 939px) 100vw, 939px" data-lazy-src=3D"https://ovacen.com/wp-content/=
uploads/2025/01/formulas-for-calculating-sphere-volume.jpg">
</picture>
<figcaption id=3D"caption-attachment-45161" class=3D"wp-caption-text">By OV=
ACEN</figcaption></figure>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">The volume of a sphere is measured in cub=
ic units, such as cubic meters (m=C2=B3), cubic centimeters (cm=C2=B3), or =
cubic inches (in=C2=B3). And the formula to calculate the volume is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>To calculate the volume of a sphere with the radius, the formula is: Vo=
lume =3D (4/3) =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 radius=C2=B3</li>
<li>To calculate the volume of a sphere with the diameter, the formula is: =
Volume =3D (4/3) =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 (diameter/2)=C2=B3</li>
<li>To calculate the volume of a sphere with the circumference, the formula=
 is: Volume =3D Circumference=C2=B3 / (6 x (=CF=80=C2=B2))</li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=9F=A7 <strong>Note:</strong> The formula to calculate the volume =
of a sphere is universal, and remember that Pi number =3D =CF=80 is approxi=
mately 3.1416</p>
<h4><strong>Example of calculating the volume of a sphere:</strong></h4>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>If we have a sphere with a radius of 5 cm, we would apply the following=
 calculation: Volume =3D (4/3) =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 (5 cm)=C2=B3 =E2=89=88 =
523.6 cm=C2=B3.</li>
<li>If we know the diameter of a sphere, for example, 10 cm, first we divid=
e the diameter by 2 to obtain the radius (5 cm). We apply the formula to ca=
lculate the volume and obtain the same result of 523.6 cm=C2=B3.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">We also provide the following educational=
 video to learn both the mathematical formula, geometry concepts, the diffe=
rences between surface and volume, and <strong>how to calculate the volume =
of a sphere</strong>:</p>
<p></p><div class=3D"rll-youtube-player" data-src=3D"https://www.youtube.co=
m/embed/QvP6dZZfaU8" data-id=3D"QvP6dZZfaU8" data-query=3D"si=3DNms3zHp_oNv=
-hL6A" data-alt=3D"YouTube video player"><div data-id=3D"QvP6dZZfaU8" data-=
query=3D"si=3DNms3zHp_oNv-hL6A" data-src=3D"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Q=
vP6dZZfaU8"><img data-lazy-src=3D"https://i.ytimg.com/vi/QvP6dZZfaU8/hqdefa=
ult.jpg" alt=3D"YouTube video player" width=3D"480" height=3D"360"><button =
class=3D"play" aria-label=3D"Play Youtube video" data-rocket-onclick=3D"thi=
s.rocketonclick(event)"></button></div></div><p></p>
<blockquote><p>It=E2=80=99s important to note that the volume of a sphere i=
s exactly two-thirds the volume of the circumscribed cylinder (the smallest=
 cylinder that can contain the sphere).</p></blockquote>
<h4><strong>What units can you use in the calculator to calculate the volum=
e of a sphere?</strong></h4>
<p>The <strong>calculator to obtain the capacity of a sphere</strong> allow=
s entering values in the following units:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
&nbsp;	<p></p>
<li>Millimeters (mm) =E2=86=92 Cubic Millimeters (mm=C2=B3)</li>
<p>&nbsp;	</p>
